{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619465"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:31:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:31:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16555"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16555"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.64,0.07,0.11,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74742"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9246"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16555"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60227"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1708"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2572"},{"type":"tags","id":"3575"},{"type":"tags","id":"3945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5931"},{"type":"tags","id":"10359"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21905"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21909"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74742"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset vertigo, difficulty swallowing, and left-sided facial numbness. She has a history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. Her medications include Amlodipine and Atorvastatin. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. She has left-sided Horner syndrome, right-sided decreased pain and temperature sensation of the body, and left-sided decreased pain and temperature sensation of the face. Her gait is ataxic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following arteries is most likely to be occluded in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superior cerebellar artery","Posterior inferior cerebellar artery","Posterior spinal artery","Posterior communicating artery","Anterior inferior cerebellar artery"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of lateral medullary (Wallenberg) syndrome, which occurs due to occlusion of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior inferior cerebellar artery (PICA)\u003C/strong\u003E. PICA is the largest branch of the vertebral artery and supplies the posterior cerebellar hemisphere, dorsolateral medulla, and choroid plexus of the fourth ventricle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior cerebellar artery\u003C/strong\u003E arises from the basilar artery and supplies the superior surface of the cerebellum. Its occlusion would not cause the constellation of symptoms seen in lateral medullary syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior spinal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the posterior third of the spinal cord. Occlusion would result in a posterior cord syndrome with loss of proprioception and vibration sense below the level of the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior communicating artery\u003C/strong\u003E connects the posterior cerebral and internal carotid arteries, forming part of the Circle of Willis. Its occlusion typically does not cause significant symptoms due to collateral circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior inferior cerebellar artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the anteroinferior portion of the cerebellum and part of the pons. Its occlusion causes a different syndrome characterised by ipsilateral facial weakness, deafness, and ataxia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe classic features of Wallenberg syndrome include ipsilateral Horner syndrome, ipsilateral facial sensory loss, contralateral body sensory loss, ipsilateral cerebellar signs, and dysphagia. These symptoms occur due to involvement of various structures in the lateral medulla including the descending sympathetic tract, spinal trigeminal nucleus, spinothalamic tract, and vestibular nuclei.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The posterior inferior cerebellar artery (PICA) is the largest branch of the vertebral artery.","PICA supplies the posterior cerebellar hemisphere, dorsolateral medulla, and choroid plexus of the fourth ventricle.","Occlusion of PICA results in lateral medullary (Wallenberg) syndrome."],"references":["Singh RK, Behari S, Kumar V, Jaiswal AK, Jain VK. Posterior inferior cerebellar artery aneurysms: Anatomical variations and surgical strategies. Asian J Neurosurg. 2012 Jan;7(1):2-11. doi: 10.4103/1793-5482.95687. PMID: 22639684; PMCID: PMC3358952.","Miao HL, Zhang DY, Wang T, Jiao XT, Jiao LQ. Clinical Importance of the Posterior Inferior Cerebellar Artery: A Review of the Literature. Int J Med Sci. 2020 Oct 18;17(18):3005-3019. doi: 10.7150/ijms.49137. PMID: 33173421; PMCID: PMC7646108.","B\u0142aszczyk M, Ochwat K, Necka S, Kwieci\u0144ska M, Ostrowski P, Bonczar M, \u017bytkowski A, Walocha J, Mitu\u015b J, Koziej M. The Arterial Anatomy of the Cerebellum-A Comprehensive Review. Brain Sci. 2024 Jul 29;14(8):763. doi: 10.3390/brainsci14080763. PMID: 39199457; PMCID: PMC11352334.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60227"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16555"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60227"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T18:33:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T18:33:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9246"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74742"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre